{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3cf683e3-897e-4bd1-acd3-f1806b8e2377","content":"On macOS, when a process crashes the system automatically generates a **crash report**. Look here:\n\n1. **User-level reports:**  \n   `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n2. **System-level reports:**  \n   `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\nFiles are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`. You can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them.\n\nFor a full **core dump**, macOS disables them by default. To enable:\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n/usr/libexec/PlistBuddy -c \"Add :com.apple.CrashReporter.UseNewCrashPath bool false\" ~/Library/Preferences/com.apple.CrashReporter.plist\n```\n\nThen re-run your app — the core file will appear in `/cores/core.<pid>`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"67d6b20b-6a10-47bd-90fc-eb7f24efdd34","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":288},"id":"a3a4e96d-24df-4529-b502-df9d85055f5d","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:58:25.789Z","parentId":"2cd7f0eb-e1d4-45e4-bd98-292fa2979d11"}
